# Extract day, month, day of week and day of year from Date.
def get_temporal_features(df, date_col, id_col):
      temp = df[[id_col, date_col]]
      # Get Day of Week
      temp['DoW'] = temp[date_col].dt.day_name()
      # Get Month Name
      temp['Month'] = temp[date_col].dt.month_name()
      # One hot encode using dummies
      dummies = pd.get_dummies(temp[['DoW', 'Month']])
      dummies[id_col] = df[id_col].values
      # Aggregate by customer
      dummies = dummies.groupby(id_col).sum() 
      return dummies

def customer_frequency(data, cut_off, date_column, customer_id_column, value_column, freq='M'):
    # Get data before cut off
    frequency = data[data[date_column] < cut_off].copy()
    frequency.set_index(date_column, inplace=True)
    frequency.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(frequency.index)
    # Group transactions by customer key
    frequency = frequency.groupby([customer_id_column, pd.Grouper(freq=freq, level=date_column)]).count()
    frequency[value_column] = 1 # Store all distinct transactions
    # Sum distinct transactions
    return frequency.groupby(customer_id_column).sum().reset_index().rename(
    columns={value_column : 'frequency'}
      )

def customer_recency(data, cut_off, date_column, customer_id_column):
  # Get data before cut off
    recency = data[data[date_column] < cut_off].copy()
    recency[date_column] = pd.to_datetime(recency[date_column])
  # Group customers by latest transaction
    recency = recency.groupby(customer_id_column)[date_column].max()
    return ((pd.to_datetime(cut_off) - recency).dt.days).reset_index().rename(
    columns={date_column : 'recency'}
  )

def customer_age(data, cut_off, date_column, customer_id_column):
    age = data[data[date_column] < cut_off]
    first_purchase = age.groupby(customer_id_column)[date_column].min().reset_index()
  # Get number of days between cut off and first transaction
    first_purchase['age'] = (cut_off - first_purchase[date_column]).dt.days
    return first_purchase[[customer_id_column, 'age']]

# This function simply wraps up all the others into a single function to 
# to perform the feature engineering
def customer_rfm(data, cut_off, date_column, customer_id_column, value_column, freq='M'):
    cut_off = pd.to_datetime(cut_off)
  # Compute Recency
    recency = customer_recency(data, cut_off, date_column, customer_id_column)
  # Compute Frequency
    frequency = customer_frequency(data, cut_off, date_column, customer_id_column, value_column, freq=freq)
  # Compute age
    age = customer_age(data, cut_off, date_column, customer_id_column)
  # Merge all columns
    return recency.merge(frequency, on=customer_id_column).merge(age, on=customer_id_column)

#silhouette method for sample ~100000
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

sil = []
kmax = range(2,20)
# dissimilarity would not be defined for a single cluster, thus, minimum number of clusters should be 2
for k in kmax:
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k).fit(abc)
        labels = kmeans.labels_
        sil.append(silhouette_score(abc, labels, metric = 'euclidean'))
        print(sil)

#silhouette method for 25% ~200000
range_n_clusters= list(range(2,10))
for n_clusters in range_n_clusters:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict(abc)
    centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_

    score = silhouette_score(abc, preds)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {})".format(n_clusters, score))

#K means elbow method for sample ~25% --> 200000
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler().fit(abc)
_features = pd.DataFrame(
    scaler.transform(abc),
    columns = abc.columns,
    index=abc.index
)
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

sq_distances = []
K = range(1,20)
for k in K:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    km = km.fit(_features)
    sq_distances.append(km.inertia_)
In [115]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
ax.plot(K, sq_distances)
plt.ylabel('Sum of Squared Distances')
plt.xlabel('Clusters')
plt.show()

#for sample data of 100000 records. ~ran for approx 17mins

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
# !pip install yellowbrick
from yellowbrick.cluster import SilhouetteVisualizer

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(15,8))
for i in [2, 3, 4, 5,6,7,8]:
    '''
    Create KMeans instances for different number of clusters
    '''
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', n_init=10, max_iter=100, random_state=42)
    q, mod = divmod(i, 2)
    '''
    Create SilhouetteVisualizer instance with KMeans instance
    Fit the visualizer
    '''
    visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(km, colors='yellowbrick', ax=ax[q-1][mod])
    visualizer.fit(abc)

import numpy as np

cm1 = cm[['recency', 'frequency', 'age']]
# Melting the dataframe to create a new column for the variables
df_melted = cm1.melt(var_name='Column', value_name='Value', ignore_index=False).reset_index()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))

# Plotting the bar plot using seaborn with custom color palette
sns_plot = sns.barplot(x='Column', y='Value', hue='index', data=df_melted, dodge=True, palette=colors, ax=ax)

# Adding value annotations to the bars with values greater than 100
for i in range(len(cm1.columns)):
    col = cm1.columns[i]
    for idx, patch in enumerate(sns_plot.patches[i::len(cm1.columns)]):
        # Set the position of the annotation to the center of the bar
        x = patch.get_x() + patch.get_width() / 2
        y = patch.get_height()
        value = cm1[col].iloc[idx]
        label = '{:.2f}'.format(value)
        sns_plot.text(x, y+y*0.01, label, ha='center', va='bottom', color='black', rotation=53)

Looking at their comments and understaing that sentiment could be further helpful to understand if they had a very bad experience ?¶

2) Cluster 1 age and recency is the same which is also pretty low meaning that they are new customers. Should we be giving them incentives to turn them into potential permanent ones. Its second smallest group.¶

3)Cluster 2 has highest frequency and a recency of around 1 year even with thier age being around 8 years ago. It is the smallest cluster. These customers seem the most reliable ones and seem to show consistency. Could check prd_type/prd_subtype of these customers if they have mostly multi-ride tickets or not.¶

4) Cluster 3 and 4 are nearly same size and have nearly same recency. However, cluster 4 has second highest frequency for our data and are the ones with the oldest age. Cluster 3 has second best recency and a good age as well but the frequency is pretty low. However, since both these groups have high age and decent recency, which means they have been continuing with Amtrak but just not a lot. We could market towards them to increase their frequency.¶

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Filter out rows where the mail_addr_state_cd column is "unknown"
cluster_2_data_filtered = cluster_2_data[cluster_2_data["loc_state_prov_cd"] != "unknown"]

# Compute the value counts for each state
state_counts = cluster_2_data_filtered["loc_state_prov_cd"].value_counts().reset_index()
state_counts.columns = ["State", "Count"]

# Load the U.S. state code data
state_codes = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/plotly/datasets/master/2011_us_ag_exports.csv")

# Merge the value counts data with the state code data
merged_data = pd.merge(state_codes, state_counts, left_on="code", right_on="State", how="left")

# Create the choropleth map plot using plotly
fig = px.choropleth(
    merged_data, 
    locations="code", 
    color="Count",
    scope="usa",
    locationmode="USA-states",
    color_continuous_scale="Greens",
    title="Value Counts by State",
    custom_data=["State", "Count"]
)

fig.update_layout(
    coloraxis_colorbar=dict(title="Value Count"), 
    coloraxis_colorbar_len=0.8,
    coloraxis=dict(colorscale="Greens", reversescale=False),
    geo=dict(scope="usa", projection_scale=3, center=dict(lat=37.0902, lon=-95.7129)), 
    title=dict(text="Value Counts by State", x=0.5), 
    margin=dict(l=0, r=0, t=50, b=0), 
    hoverlabel=dict(bgcolor="white", font_size=12, font_family="Arial")
)

fig.update_traces(
    hovertemplate="<b>%{customdata[0]}</b><br>" + 
                  "Value Count: %{customdata[1]}<br>" + 
                  "<extra></extra>"
)

fig.show()
fig.write_html('cluster2_top_departure_states.html')

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Get the top 10 states by count in 'route_nm' column
top_states = cluster_2_negative_comments['route_nm'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index.tolist()

# Filter the dataframe to only include the top 10 states
df_top_states = cluster_2_negative_comments[cluster_2_negative_comments['route_nm'].isin(top_states)]

# Get the top 10 categories by count in 'cmnt_rsn_typ_cd' column
top_categories = cluster_2_negative_comments['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index.tolist()

# Filter the dataframe to only include the top 10 categories
df_top_categories = cluster_2_negative_comments[cluster_2_negative_comments['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].isin(top_categories)]

# Filter the dataframe to only include rows with both top states and top categories
df_top = df_top_states[df_top_states['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].isin(top_categories)]

# Calculate the percentage of each category for each state
df_perc = df_top.groupby(['route_nm', 'cmnt_rsn_typ_cd']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
df_perc['percentage'] = df_perc.groupby('route_nm')['counts'].apply(lambda x: 100 * x / x.sum())

# Pivot the data to a wide format for plotting
df_pivot = df_perc.pivot(index='route_nm', columns='cmnt_rsn_typ_cd', values='percentage')

# Convert 'route_nm' to a categorical column and order the categories based on their frequency
df_top_states['route_nm'] = pd.Categorical(df_top_states['route_nm'], categories=top_states, ordered=True)
df_top_states = df_top_states.sort_values('route_nm')

# Create the stacked bar plot
fig = px.bar(df_pivot, barmode='stack', orientation='h', color_discrete_sequence=px.colors.qualitative.Set2, title='Percentage of Comment Reason Types by Route Names', labels={'value': 'Percentage', 'route_nm': 'Route Names'})
fig.update_layout(showlegend=True)
fig.update_xaxes(showticklabels=True)
fig.update_yaxes(showticklabels=True)

# Add value counts to customdata for each category
for col in df_pivot.columns:
    fig.data[df_pivot.columns.get_loc(col)].update(customdata=df_top_states['route_nm'].value_counts().loc[df_pivot.index].tolist())

# Add hover information
fig.update_traces(hovertemplate='%{label}<br>Percentage of cmnt reason: %{x:.2f}%<br>Value Count of Route Name: %{customdata}')

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Get the top 10 states by count in 'route_nm' column
top_routes = cluster_2_negative_comments['route_nm'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index.tolist()

# Filter the dataframe to only include the top 10 states
df_top_routes = cluster_2_negative_comments[cluster_2_negative_comments['route_nm'].isin(top_routes)]

# Get the top 10 categories by count in 'cmnt_rsn_typ_cd' column
top_categories = cluster_2_negative_comments['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index.tolist()

# Filter the dataframe to only include the top 10 categories
df_top_categories = cluster_2_negative_comments[cluster_2_negative_comments['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].isin(top_categories)]

# Filter the dataframe to only include rows with both top states and top categories
df_top = df_top_routes[df_top_routes['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].isin(top_categories)]

# Calculate the percentage of each category for each state and sort by descending percentage
df_perc = df_top.groupby(['route_nm', 'cmnt_rsn_typ_cd']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
df_perc = df_perc.sort_values(by=['route_nm', 'counts'], ascending=[True, False])
df_perc['percentage'] = df_perc.groupby('route_nm')['counts'].apply(lambda x: 100 * x / x.sum())

# Pivot the data to a wide format for plotting
df_pivot = df_perc.pivot(index='route_nm', columns='cmnt_rsn_typ_cd', values='percentage')

# Sort the dataframe by the sum of each column in descending order
df_pivot = df_pivot[df_pivot.sum().sort_values(ascending=False).index]

# Set the order of categories for plotting
category_orders = {
    'cmnt_rsn_typ_cd': list(df_pivot.columns)
}

# Define a color map for the categories
color_map = {
    'category1': 'red',
    'category2': 'blue',
    'category3': 'green',
    'category4': 'orange',
    'category5': 'purple',
    'category6': 'pink',
    'category7': 'brown',
    'category8': 'gray',
    'category9': 'yellow',
    'category10': 'cyan'
}

# Convert 'route_nm' to a categorical column and order the categories based on their frequency
df_top_routes['route_nm'] = pd.Categorical(df_top_routes['route_nm'], categories=top_routes, ordered=True)
df_top_routes = df_top_routes.sort_values('route_nm')

# Create the stacked bar plot
fig = px.bar(df_pivot, barmode='stack', orientation='h', color_discrete_map=color_map, title='Percentage of Comment Reason Types by Route Names', labels={'value': 'Percentage', 'route_nm': 'Route Names'}, category_orders=category_orders)
fig.update_layout(showlegend=True)
fig.update_xaxes(showticklabels=True)
fig.update_yaxes(showticklabels=True)

# Add value counts to customdata for each category
for col in df_pivot.columns:
    fig.data[df_pivot.columns.get_loc(col)].update(customdata=df_top_routes['route_nm'].value_counts().loc[df_pivot.index].tolist())

# Add hover information
fig.update_traces(hovertemplate='%{label}<br><b>Percentage of cmnt reason: %{x:.2f}%</b><br>Value Count of Route Name: %{customdata}')

fig.show()
fig.write_html('cluster2_perc_cmnt_reason_routewise.html')

sns_plot = sns.barplot(x='Column', y='Value', hue='index', data=df_melted, dodge=True, palette=colors, ax=ax)

# Adding value annotations to the bars with values greater than 100
for i in range(len(cm2.columns)):
    col = cm2.columns[i]
    for idx, patch in enumerate(sns_plot.patches[i::len(cm2.columns)]):
        # Set the position of the annotation to the center of the bar
        x = patch.get_x() + patch.get_width() / 2
        y = patch.get_height()
        value = cm2[col].iloc[idx]
        if value > 0:
            label = '{:.2f}'.format(value)
            sns_plot.text(x, y+y*0.01, label, ha='center', va='bottom', color='black', rotation=0)

# Setting the title and labels for the plot
plt.title('Cluster wise bar plot for revenue amnt features')
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Mean-values')

# Moving the legend to the top left of the plot
sns_plot.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(0.75, 1.2), ncol=5)

# Setting the style of the plot
sns.set_style('darkgrid')

# Displaying the plot
plt.show()

# Load the U.S. state code data

# Merge the value counts data with the state code data

    merged_data, 
    locations="code", 
    color="Count",
    scope="usa",
    locationmode="USA-states",
    color_continuous_scale="Greens",
    title="Departures by State in Cluster 1",
    custom_data=["State", "Count"]
)

    coloraxis_colorbar_len=0.8,
    coloraxis=dict(colorscale="blues", reversescale=False),
    geo=dict(scope="usa", projection_scale=3, center=dict(lat=37.0902, lon=-95.7129)), 
    title=dict(text="Departures by State in Cluster 1", x=0.5), 
    margin=dict(l=0, r=0, t=50, b=0), 
    hoverlabel=dict(bgcolor="white", font_size=12, font_family="Arial")
)

fig.update_traces(
    hovertemplate="<b>%{customdata[0]}</b><br>" + 
                  "Value Count: %{customdata[1]}<br>" + 
                  "<extra></extra>"
)

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Get the top 10 states by count in 'route_nm' column
top_routes = cluster_2_positive_comments['route_nm'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index.tolist()

# Filter the dataframe to only include the top 10 states
df_top_routes = cluster_2_positive_comments[cluster_2_positive_comments['route_nm'].isin(top_routes)]

# Get the top 10 categories by count in 'cmnt_rsn_typ_cd' column
top_categories = cluster_2_positive_comments['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index.tolist()

# Filter the dataframe to only include the top 10 categories
df_top_categories = cluster_2_positive_comments[cluster_2_positive_comments['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].isin(top_categories)]

# Filter the dataframe to only include rows with both top states and top categories
df_top = df_top_routes[df_top_routes['cmnt_rsn_typ_cd'].isin(top_categories)]

# Calculate the percentage of each category for each state and sort by descending percentage
df_perc = df_top.groupby(['route_nm', 'cmnt_rsn_typ_cd']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
df_perc = df_perc.sort_values(by=['route_nm', 'counts'], ascending=[True, False])
df_perc['percentage'] = df_perc.groupby('route_nm')['counts'].apply(lambda x: 100 * x / x.sum())

# Pivot the data to a wide format for plotting
df_pivot = df_perc.pivot(index='route_nm', columns='cmnt_rsn_typ_cd', values='percentage')

# Sort the dataframe by the sum of each column in descending order
df_pivot = df_pivot[df_pivot.sum().sort_values(ascending=False).index]

# Set the order of categories for plotting
category_orders = {
    'cmnt_rsn_typ_cd': list(df_pivot.columns)
}

# Define a color map for the categories
color_map = {
    'category1': 'red',
    'category2': 'blue',
    'category3': 'green',
    'category4': 'orange',
    'category5': 'purple',
    'category6': 'pink',
    'category7': 'brown',
    'category8': 'gray',
    'category9': 'yellow',
    'category10': 'cyan'
}

# Convert 'route_nm' to a categorical column and order the categories based on their frequency
df_top_routes['route_nm'] = pd.Categorical(df_top_routes['route_nm'], categories=top_routes, ordered=True)
df_top_routes = df_top_routes.sort_values('route_nm')

# Create the stacked bar plot
fig = px.bar(df_pivot, barmode='stack', orientation='h', color_discrete_map=color_map, title='Percentage of Comment Reason Types by Route Names', labels={'value': 'Percentage', 'route_nm': 'Route Names'}, category_orders=category_orders)
fig.update_layout(showlegend=True)
fig.update_xaxes(showticklabels=True)
fig.update_yaxes(showticklabels=True)

# Add value counts to customdata for each category
for col in df_pivot.columns:
    fig.data[df_pivot.columns.get_loc(col)].update(customdata=df_top_routes['route_nm'].value_counts().loc[df_pivot.index].tolist())

# Add hover information
fig.update_traces(hovertemplate='%{label}<br><b>Percentage of cmnt reason: %{x:.2f}%</b><br>Value Count of Route Name: %{customdata}')

fig.show()
